Title: Norwegian Wood
Author: Haruki Murakami
My Review:
Watanabe really acts like is life is lame, but then he recalls his life and it's really wild. And then you read the book and you're like not a lot happens in this book but then you finish it and look back and realise a lot happened. It's crazy. This book is crazy, like it really made an impression on me and I don't even know why.
It's just a book about sex and suicide, and japanese teens like it for some reason.

Also wow I wish I was a lame nerdy sex god with tons of manic pixie dream girls swooning over me.

Title: The Wind-Up Bird Chronicle
Author: Haruki Murakami
My Review:
this is a book about a dumb stupid man with no personality, who keeps taking L's. but he doesn't care about all the L's he takes because his only personality trait is apathy.
luckily Murakami saves this character by placing him in a surreal, philosophical plotline. it's a bit too weird sometimes, like it's just weird for the sake of being weird. i enjoyed it tho.

Title: If on a Winter's Night a Traveler
Author: Italo Calvino
My Review:
You're sitting in your house, bored during quarantine. You desperately wish you had something to read. So you walk up to your bookshelf, examining the spine of each book. One book in particular catches your eyes, "If on a winter's night a traveller". You open the book and begin to read...

yada, yada, that's basically the whole gimmick. It's wonderfully executed tho, and the book is a joy to read even if you know about the gimmick, and even if you know the wacky plot beforehand.

also sidenote, the reader be like:
"a girl.... AND a reader? Whoa mama! *eyes pop out of sockets* AWOOGA! *jaw drops to the floor* ahem, please let me discuss books with you"
